Not picking on Gunner in CA, but his reply got me thinking about the term reverse migration. Typically, fall winter is a southern migration and late winter spring is a north migration. Isn’t a reverse migration when movement is opposite the typical pattern? I guess snows are the best example as they chase the snow line, but I think all waterfowl does at times based on weather. Just curious what your thoughts are.
Reverse Migration Snows and Sandhills headed north the last few days flying over my house in the afternoon and evening. March 3rd

Snows have entered this region Sat-Sun 3/5-3/6. Very spotty in terms of numbers. This morning (tue 3/8) saw small groups of approx 12-24 dropping in on few fields and all groups were heading from North to South. Got 3-4” snow last night and looks like a mild reverse migration happening.

The snow goose migration is basically non-existent in Boone County, Iowa right now; heard one large flock of snows fly over at night, otherwise nothing. With this cold weather were having hopefully the birds will stay to the south of us; it’s always nice when they wait until spring break to come through

Increasing flocks and larger flocks along the SD/NE border on the Missouri River. There is open water downstream of Gavins Point Dam and Lake Yankton (immediately below the dam) has lots of open water. The 2 inches of snow that we got on Saturday will not last long with all this sunshine.

several small groups (families) of dark geese passing thru the past several days. Large groups of Specks with a few snows mixed in higher then kites moved thru during the past week. Any snows been found in the Sioux City to Hawarden area along the Sioux River?
Seems to be coming North then going west overhead.

We didn't see anything Saturday morning. Didn't except to see much this morning so we slept in and was planning on just pulling decoys this morning. Got to lake at 9:30 and there was 30k in the field, 200 yards from our decoys. Was covered up with non-working birds all day. We finally gave up at 2pm. 31 degrees and cloudy today. Good migration day, fighting the north wind. They was flying all directions today and puring in from the south. I"m guessing Squak lost a lot of geese today
